Heres what could be happening and how to address it:

### 1. Theme Configuration
**First**, double check these values in your `themes.xml` (both `res/values/themes.xml` and `res/values-night/themes.xml` for night mode):

```xml
<item name="android:statusBarColor">@android:color/transparent</item>
<item name="android:windowTranslucentStatus">true</item>
<item name="android:windowDrawsSystemBarBackgrounds">true</item>
```
Sometimes, using `windowTranslucentStatus` together with `statusBarColor` is necessary.

### 2. Code-level Override
Calling `enableEdgeToEdge()` and using `window` modifications (like `SystemBarUtil.hideNavigationBar(window = this.window)`) can affect system bar colors. If any Composable or activity fragment sets the system bar color programmatically, it will override the XML settings.

### 3. Compose & System UI Overlays
If using Jetpack Compose (which you are, via `setContent { ComposeView() }`), you likely need to also set the system bar appearance in Compose. Many Jetpack Compose apps use `SystemUiController` from the `accompanist-systemuicontroller` library.

Example (in your Composable):

```kotlin
val systemUiController = rememberSystemUiController()
SideEffect {
 systemUiController.setStatusBarColor(
 color = Color.Transparent,
 darkIcons = true // or false, depending on your foreground
 )
}
```
Make sure you dont have earlier calls that set the status bar color (including default colors in your Compose theme).

### 4. Home Screen Specificity
Check if your Home screens compose function or activity is setting the status bar color elsewhere.

